{"version":2,"kind":"Article","sha256":"bde9ecba9ec1065c4dc4146a2f29a5672e09ec47bcf7df6854feb3ca23efed83","slug":"czsfieldmethods","location":"/22CZSFieldMethods.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"2.2 Field and Lab Analyses","content_includes_title":false,"thumbnail":"/f2e1cc75f807f749623a0dbb11b8a61e.jpeg","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"22CZSFieldMethods.md","url":"/22CZSFieldMethods-fbb093f61452616ec23ac7b9b3f87a8b.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Studying the Critical Zone (CZ) involves exploring unique research questions, testing hypotheses, and designing experiments. A key objective for researchers is to establish common measurements that can be used to compare CZ processes and functions across various study sites. Using common measurements, the collective insights gained from the network of research efforts become more significant than the sum of their findings.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"DmSjKWgjkL"}],"key":"uyDRtHKf0O"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Some of the methods employed in this research include carbon isotopes, rock and soil profile weathering rates, stream discharge measurements, demographic studies, and soil carbon assessments. Additionally, research activities encompass data analysis and communication, leveraging actual data to understand CZ processes and consider human interactions within the CZ framework.","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"arMzXNANkH"}],"key":"mHuSke20JJ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"CZ scientists aim to quantify, using a shared set of measurements, the following:","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"e0WyMyTPt8"}],"key":"F2HSqJL9Wp"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The structure and evolution of the CZ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"O6dULpkUhj"}],"key":"aXJCPNLfoS"}],"key":"ZWUmvjeTfr"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Event-based and continuous fluxes across CZ interfaces","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"fttBqWILFY"}],"key":"LuKsQXtLWZ"}],"key":"oF45PvXiM4"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":13,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Changes in budgets related to energy, water, solutes, and sediment","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"j19iF1hq6N"}],"key":"H1rUjo6mOW"}],"key":"hWYQ92zEEf"}],"key":"CJpj105izp"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/f2e1cc75f807f749623a0dbb11b8a61e.jpeg","alt":"The infrastructure used to study the Earth’s CZ—the layer between the forest canopy and the base of weathered bedrock. Image source: No soils, no life | NSF","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"YJxBFVWvHg","urlSource":"https://nsf-gov-resources.nsf.gov/styles/_inline_image_full_width/s3/2020-10/2_critical_zone_observatory_eaf5ec54-ce22-4251-ad25-84debc86a0b0.jpg"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"cz-infrastructure","identifier":"cz-infrastructure","html_id":"cz-infrastructure","enumerator":"1","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"bHJwQS1gpH"},{"type":"text","value":"1","key":"PZHmRWLTYL"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"SrrEFRCOwt"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"vHVinAdbto"},{"type":"text","value":"The infrastructure used to study the Earth’s CZ—the layer between the forest canopy and the base of weathered bedrock. Image source: ","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"P5YYlLXRMr"},{"type":"link","url":"https://beta.nsf.gov/science-matters/no-soils-no-life?linkId=102003605","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"No soils, no life | NSF","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"v5VGUzvbza"}],"urlSource":"https://beta.nsf.gov/science-matters/no-soils-no-life?linkId=102003605","key":"dQe5s4csFH"}],"key":"XOHjCROdbO"}],"key":"yR2yCdL5op"}],"class":"margin-caption","label":"cz-infrastructure","identifier":"cz-infrastructure","enumerator":"1","html_id":"cz-infrastructure","key":"DuUysAnuz1"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Below are examples of the methods used to collect various types of data.","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"doK8OyIVZN"}],"key":"ezvrtix2B2"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Land-Atmosphere Interface","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"OObcY0THMK"}],"identifier":"land-atmosphere-interface","label":"Land-Atmosphere Interface","html_id":"land-atmosphere-interface","implicit":true,"key":"KWC57Yi3ud"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Energy and materials are exchanged in various forms between the land and the atmosphere. The primary materials involved in these exchanges are carbon and water. One advanced research instrument commonly used in Critical Zone Observatories (CZOs) is the eddy covariance or flux tower.","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"CTJJb0g0Im"}],"key":"FDOQfihNyi"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"An eddy covariance tower is an atmospheric measurement device that quantifies the exchange of carbon dioxide, water vapor, and energy between the land surface and the atmosphere. It typically consists of a tall tower equipped with multiple instruments, including sensors for measuring wind speed and direction, temperature, humidity, and atmospheric pressure. The data collected by an eddy flux tower provides valuable insights into the processes that control the exchange of energy, water, and carbon between the land and the atmosphere. This information is crucial for understanding the Earth’s carbon cycle and the impacts of climate change.","position":{"start":{"line":28,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"key":"j2YZi4rC7K"}],"key":"zU1HUqRi9u"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/CR4Anc8Mkas","width":"100%","key":"NtKj3WrWJc"}],"key":"eb094r8EOz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The NSF-funded National Ecological Observatory Network (NEON) has installed several eddy covariance towers across the United States. These towers are in “ecoclimatic domains,” representing distinct regions characterized by different vegetation types, landforms, and ecosystem dynamics. This setup allows NEON to capture the full range of ecological and climatic diversity found in the country (see ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"j5qCays1zM"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.neonscience.org/","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"NSF NEON | Open Data to Understand Our Ecosystems","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"P7KMil5JGy"}],"urlSource":"https://www.neonscience.org/","key":"vwzOkvKayz"},{"type":"text","value":"). The data collected from these observatories is available through the ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"HOlPlUlqQ8"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.neonscience.org/data","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Data Portal | NSF NEON","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"nebiWj9o4I"}],"urlSource":"https://www.neonscience.org/data","key":"SV9iSgZ0bP"},{"type":"text","value":" and can serve as an excellent supplement to data from nearby Critical Zone Observatories (CZOs).","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"ecioQ3DZWi"}],"key":"LVFzTdISu2"},{"type":"container","kind":"figure","children":[{"type":"image","url":"/e034977931253cf7537657e2b1a91861.png","alt":"Field sites operated by NSF-funded NEON across the US. Image source: Field Sites | NSF NEON","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"dzkv3kxWo0","urlSource":"https://www.neonscience.org/sites/default/files/styles/max_1300x1300/public/2021-04/2021_04_Graphic_Domain_Map%20Field%20sites_w_rivers_png.png"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"captionNumber","kind":"figure","label":"neon-sites","identifier":"neon-sites","html_id":"neon-sites","enumerator":"2","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Figure ","key":"ckhVBFWIDd"},{"type":"text","value":"2","key":"ZtixFxe4e1"},{"type":"text","value":":","key":"kGXiK2XKP4"}],"template":"Figure %s:","key":"U7bk2Szy3M"},{"type":"text","value":"Field sites operated by NSF-funded NEON across the US. Image source: ","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"wV7cSPKXhy"},{"type":"link","url":"https://www.neonscience.org/field-sites","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Field Sites | NSF NEON","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"D4OQntDzPj"}],"urlSource":"https://www.neonscience.org/field-sites","key":"PZ4qHwavq7"}],"key":"myPfD7z24G"}],"key":"xqxf8uAWWH"}],"class":"margin-caption","label":"neon-sites","identifier":"neon-sites","enumerator":"2","html_id":"neon-sites","key":"yZpdQojbRv"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The eddy covariance method is frequently used after a detailed landscape assessment, often involving remote sensing techniques such as LiDAR (light detection and ranging). These techniques are applicable in various fields, including archaeology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, and self-driving vehicle technologies.","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"zQMof8rfVf"}],"key":"SWzr7hkHla"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/chSywRqgIGY","width":"100%","key":"F0Iu1j5eEJ"}],"key":"KmRh3RGDR9"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Vegetation and Associated Microbiota","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1},"end":{"line":54,"column":1}},"key":"uWDDhBC6x3"}],"identifier":"vegetation-and-associated-microbiota","label":"Vegetation and Associated Microbiota","html_id":"vegetation-and-associated-microbiota","implicit":true,"key":"bCSDONmLG5"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Carbon from dead, decaying animals and rotting leaves eventually enters the atmosphere. To understand this crucial carbon cycling process, we must explore three key aspects of soil: what lives in it, what it is made of, and how it behaves under different environmental conditions.","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1},"end":{"line":56,"column":1}},"key":"qEoJ5IKEOw"}],"key":"F9xWuLDpyV"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When we stand on soil, we are standing on a significant reservoir of the carbon cycle, which can release large amounts of carbon into the atmosphere if global temperatures continue to rise. On the other hand, many ranchers, farmers, and soil scientists believe that soil could also help mitigate the increasing levels of atmospheric CO","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"key":"eVC6raXquu"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"_2","position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4511em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><s