storage","enumerator":"4","html_id":"soil-carbon-storage","key":"pk0DEM0CRz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"For many years, soil scientists and farmers have understood that carbon can remain in the soil for extended periods, particularly in carbon-rich humus. Humus is created when soil microbes break down soil organic material. However, humus is a complex substance that is not fully understood. Current research suggests that the duration for which soil carbon remains in humus and other soil organic matter (SOM) components depends on various ecosystem interactions involving SOM, microbes, minerals, moisture, and temperature. Scientists have not yet determined how long this carbon will stay stored in the soil or whether environmental disturbances will release significant amounts into the atmosphere, potentially exacerbating climate change.","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"o1rMIZO97h"}],"key":"jQOoxrq4S8"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/1EkkB8JaIzQ","width":"100%","key":"YkwNk6Lw7m"}],"key":"AHhsJF1dT0"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":107,"column":1},"end":{"line":107,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Soil and Vadose Zone","position":{"start":{"line":107,"column":1},"end":{"line":107,"column":1}},"key":"A1dgPOAINS"}],"identifier":"soil-and-vadose-zone","label":"Soil and Vadose Zone","html_id":"soil-and-vadose-zone","implicit":true,"key":"SpfHl90Q0K"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":109,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The solid and unsaturated phases (vadose zone) within soils provide essential information about the composition of the soil and its specific functions within the groundwater zone (CZ). The soil pit in the video below illustrates the vadose zone and the CZ.","position":{"start":{"line":109,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"key":"Oogzszcp0p"}],"key":"dSEZt7So4d"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/XzfFFNG5mnQ","width":"100%","key":"IcRZR8lVDN"}],"key":"o3c9XORmVO"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Geophysical techniques are used to study to the vadose zone in a noninvasive manner. See ","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"i5B7H4V03i"},{"type":"cite","url":"https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2014RG000465","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Multiscale geophysical imaging of the CZ - Parsekian - 2015 - Reviews of Geophysics - Wiley Online Library","position":{"start":{"line":117,"column":1},"end":{"line":117,"column":1}},"key":"scDGCqTCM0"}],"kind":"narrative","label":"Parsekian_2015","identifier":"https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1002/2014RG000465","enumerator":"1","key":"k08NSa8Do4"}],"key":"etMlON3pmy"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/Wx6-zO9aNqw","width":"100%","key":"ZfjsHb92D6"}],"key":"bLJNiarQ9W"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":123,"column":1},"end":{"line":123,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Gas sensors are also deployed to study water infiltration through the vadose zone.","position":{"start":{"line":123,"column":1},"end":{"line":123,"column":1}},"key":"UoerLbLnwj"}],"key":"QQfq87zHf6"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/_16ZMVrSmMU","width":"100%","key":"jy69yCjK4u"}],"key":"B8d86qkrca"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Saprolite and Bedrock","position":{"start":{"line":130,"column":1},"end":{"line":130,"column":1}},"key":"u24fh1aoBA"}],"identifier":"saprolite-and-bedrock","label":"Saprolite and Bedrock","html_id":"saprolite-and-bedrock","implicit":true,"key":"LIy3jDGZk3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"During the process of soil formation, bedrock weathers into regolith, which consists of weathered rock, saprolite, and soil. As this transformation occurs, porosity increases, facilitating fluid flow and releasing nutrients from the minerals present. However, these essential processes, particularly in deep regolith, are poorly understood due to the challenges of making direct observations in these areas. This is where previously mentioned geophysical techniques become valuable.","position":{"start":{"line":132,"column":1},"end":{"line":132,"column":1}},"key":"G0GSnisYO9"}],"key":"KWFD8mcCcJ"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":134,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Hollow-bore coring of bedrock enables the collection of rock and regolith samples, essential for studying this part of the critical zone (CZ). Analyzing these samples provides valuable insights into various characteristics, such as porosity, permeability, fractures, faults, and mineralogy.","position":{"start":{"line":134,"column":1},"end":{"line":134,"column":1}},"key":"x1dznh7Cbj"}],"key":"cX9KKbtd24"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/jp9m2tUiktM","width":"100%","key":"HgsB5FO7hO"}],"key":"epeIj7fmvX"},{"type":"div","class":"container","children":[{"type":"iframe","class":"video","src":"https://www.youtube.com/embed/JAhdb7dKQpU","width":"100%","key":"Ya0HuoGrVP"}],"key":"CRqwQOrFtn"},{"type":"heading",